      <hedline>
        <hl1>U.S. Marine to Resume Testimony in Japan Case</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">AP</byline>
      <dateline>TOKYO, Dec. 10</dateline>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>A marine who says the United States military forced him to falsely confess to the rape of a 12-year-old girl is to resume his testimony Monday in a Japanese court on Okinawa.</p>
        <p>Pfc. Rodrico Harp, 21, testified in the last hearing on Dec. 4 that Navy investigators dragged him out of bed before dawn and made him say he raped the girl.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>A marine who says the United States military forced him to falsely confess to the rape of a 12-year-old girl is to resume his testimony Monday in a Japanese court on Okinawa.</p>
        <p>Pfc. Rodrico Harp, 21, testified in the last hearing on Dec. 4 that Navy investigators dragged him out of bed before dawn and made him say he raped the girl.</p>
        <p>The case has outraged people on Okinawa, a southern Japanese island, and led to demands that the United States close its military bases and remove its 27,000 troops.</p>
        <p>Monday's session at the district court in Naha, Okinawa's capital, is expected to begin with further testimony by Private Harp about the confession that was supposedly forced, and cross-examination from prosecutors.</p>
        <p>Private Harp, of Griffin, Ga., and two other servicemen -- Navy Seaman Marcus Gill, 22, of Woodville, Texas, and Marine Pfc. Kendrick Ledet, 20, of Waycross,  Ga. -- are charged with rape causing injury, which carries a maximum sentence of life in prison.</p>
        <p>WORLD NEWS BRIEFS</p>
      </block>
